<EditorialPageLayout
  title="Open source · memoato"
  description="Memoato is open source: inspect the code, contribute, self-host, or adapt the personal memory layer to your needs."
  canonicalPath="/open-source"
  eyebrow="Built in the open"
  heading="Your memory should not depend on a black box."
  deck="Memoato's core is open source so the product can be inspected, adapted, self-hosted, and shaped by the people who actually use it."
  accent="ink"
>
  <p>
    Personal memory is intimate infrastructure. Openness gives you a way to understand what the software does, keep a
    copy you control, and build a version that fits needs the hosted product may never cover.
  </p>

  <h2>What open means here</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Inspect it</strong> — the application, API, data model, and product decisions are visible.</li>
    <li><strong>Contribute</strong> — report friction, suggest a better flow, or improve the code.</li>
    <li><strong>Self-host it</strong> — privacy-heavy users can run their own deployment.</li>
    <li><strong>Build on it</strong> — agents and integrations can use scoped API keys and the Memoato MCP.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>A product, not just a repository</h2>
  <p>
    The hosted Memoato experience remains the simplest path for most people. Open source is not an excuse for rough UX;
    it is a commitment to transparency and long-term user control.
  </p>

